{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":118499,"duration_api_ms":118438,"num_turns":21,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"ac037c7f-5fb9-477f-aeb6-62a3427532a1","total_cost_usd":0.6790359999999999,"usage":{"input_tokens":18,"cache_creation_input_tokens":38538,"cache_read_input_tokens":633817,"output_tokens":4847,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":38538,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":18,"outputTokens":4847,"cacheReadInputTokens":633817,"cacheCreationInputTokens":38538,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.6790359999999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"rulings":[{"amendment_id":"fr-5-f1c7b7b6","decision":"reject","rationale":"The amendment overstates the impact by claiming legacy rows are 'permanently unlinked.' The code evidence shows this is not the case. Both `backfill_running_entry` (line 2733-2748) and `backfill_terminal_entry` (line 2698-2701) accept explicit `plan_hash` from callers and will fill it in when provided — legacy rows ARE repairable through this path. The blanket prohibition against snapshot-based auto-population is an intentional safety trade-off, not a defect: the system stores no attempt-scoped provenance (no record of what `snapshot.plan_hash` was when the row was created), so at replay time it genuinely cannot distinguish 'snapshot hash unchanged since row creation' from 'snapshot hash advanced after row creation.' Without that provenance, auto-stamping from the mutable snapshot would risk mislabeling. The regression tests at service.rs:5126-5222 and 5229-5302 explicitly assert this behavior as correct and desired. The amendment's suggested fix ('compare the snapshot hash against the row's started_at') is not viable because no historical snapshot hash timeline exists. The 'permanently unlinked' claim holds only if callers perpetually omit plan_hash — but that is a caller responsibility, not a store defect, since the store correctly accepts and fills explicit plan_hash values."}],"summary":"Rejected amendment fr-5-f1c7b7b6. The blanket prohibition against snapshot-based plan_hash backfill for existing rows is an intentional safety trade-off, not a defect. The system lacks attempt-scoped provenance to safely distinguish 'snapshot unchanged' from 'snapshot advanced,' making auto-repair from the mutable snapshot unsafe. Legacy rows are NOT permanently unrepairable — both backfill_running_entry and backfill_terminal_entry accept explicit plan_hash from callers. The regression tests explicitly assert this behavior. The amendment correctly identifies a theoretical improvement (adding attempt-scoped provenance) but mischaracterizes the current safe-by-default behavior as a defect."},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"8cf546b8-1250-4b9e-8e82-b6c1183b0725"}
